/****** Object:  StoredProcedure [dbo].[fsp_Clanci_SelectById]    Script Date: 26.4.2013. 15:11:13 ******/

GO
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON
GO
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[fsp_Clanci_SelectById]
(
	@ClanakID INT
)
AS
BEGIN
	
	SET NOCOUNT ON;

	SELECT T1.*, T2.Naziv AS Vrsta, T3.Naziv AS Tema, 
	       (SELECT AVG(CONVERT(float,Ocjena))
		    FROM ClanciOcjene
		    WHERE ClanakID = T1.ClanakID) AS ProsjecnaOcjena
	FROM Clanci AS T1 INNER JOIN VrsteClanaka AS T2
	     ON T1.VrstaID = T2.VrstaID INNER JOIN Teme AS T3
	     ON T1.TemaID = T3.TemaID
	WHERE ClanakID = @ClanakID
	
END

/****** Object:  StoredProcedure [dbo].[fsp_Clanci_SelectByTypeTitle]    Script Date: 26.4.2013. 15:11:13 ******/
SET ANSI_NULLS ON
GO
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON
GO
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[fsp_Clanci_SelectByTypeTitle]
(
	@VrstaID INT = NULL,
	@Pretraga NVARCHAR(100) = NULL,
	@Offset INT,
	@MaxRows INT,
	@TotalRows INT = 0 OUTPUT
)
AS
	--SET FMTONLY OFF
	BEGIN
	CREATE TABLE #TempClanci
		(
			RedniBroj INT IDENTITY(0, 1),
			ClanakID INT
		)

	IF @VrstaID = 0
		BEGIN
			IF @Pretraga = ''
				BEGIN
					INSERT INTO #TempClanci(ClanakID)
					SELECT ClanakID
					FROM Clanci
					WHERE Status=1
					ORDER BY DatumKreiranja DESC
				END
			ELSE
				BEGIN
					INSERT INTO #TempClanci(ClanakID)
					SELECT ClanakID
					FROM Clanci
					WHERE Status=1 AND CONTAINS(Clanci.*, @Pretraga)
					ORDER BY DatumKreiranja DESC
				END
		END
	ELSE
		BEGIN
			IF @Pretraga = ''
				BEGIN
					INSERT INTO #TempClanci(ClanakID)
					SELECT ClanakID
					FROM Clanci
					WHERE Status=1 AND VrstaID = @VrstaID
					ORDER BY DatumKreiranja DESC
				END
			ELSE
				BEGIN
					INSERT INTO #TempClanci(ClanakID)
					SELECT ClanakID
					FROM Clanci
					WHERE Status=1 AND CONTAINS(Clanci.*, @Pretraga) AND VrstaID = @VrstaID
					ORDER BY DatumKreiranja DESC
				END
		END

		SELECT @TotalRows = @@ROWCOUNT

		SELECT T1.ClanakID, T1.DatumKreiranja, T1.DatumIzmjene, T1.Naslov,
		       T1.Tekst, T3.KorisnickoIme, T1.KljucneRijeci,
		       (SELECT AVG(CONVERT(float,Ocjena))
		        FROM ClanciOcjene 
		        WHERE ClanakID = T1.ClanakID) AS ProsjecnaOcjena,
			   (SELECT COUNT(ClanakKomentarID)
		        FROM ClanciKomentari 
		        WHERE ClanakID = T1.ClanakID) AS BrojKomentara
		FROM Clanci AS T1 INNER JOIN #TempClanci AS T2 
		     ON T1.ClanakID = T2.ClanakID INNER JOIN Korisnici AS T3
			 ON T1.KorisnikID = T3.KorisnikID
		WHERE  RedniBroj BETWEEN @Offset AND (@Offset + @MaxRows - 1)
		
		DROP TABLE #TempClanci

END




GO
/****** Object:  StoredProcedure [dbo].[fsp_Clanci_SelectByVrstaNazivKRijeci]    Script Date: 26.4.2013. 15:11:13 ******/
SET ANSI_NULLS ON
GO
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON
GO
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[fsp_Clanci_SelectByVrstaNazivKRijeci]
(
	@VrstaID INT = NULL,
	@Naslov NVARCHAR(100) = NULL,
	@KRijeci NVARCHAR(150) = NULL,
	@Offset INT,
	@MaxRows INT,
	@TotalRows INT = 0 OUTPUT
)
AS
BEGIN
CREATE TABLE #TempClanci
	(
		RedniBroj INT IDENTITY(0, 1),
		ClanakID INT
	)

IF @VrstaID IS NULL
	BEGIN
		INSERT INTO #TempClanci(ClanakID)
			SELECT ClanakID
			FROM Clanci
			WHERE (@Naslov = '' OR Naslov like '%' + LOWER(@Naslov) + '%') AND
				  (@KRijeci = '' OR KljucneRijeci like '%' + LOWER(@KRijeci) + '%')
			ORDER BY Naslov ASC
	END
ELSE
	BEGIN
		INSERT INTO #TempClanci(ClanakID)
			SELECT ClanakID
			FROM Clanci
			WHERE VrstaID = @VrstaID AND
				  (@Naslov = '' OR Naslov like '%' + LOWER(@Naslov) + '%') AND
				  (@KRijeci = '' OR KljucneRijeci like '%' + LOWER(@KRijeci) + '%')
			ORDER BY Naslov ASC
	END


SELECT @TotalRows = @@ROWCOUNT

SELECT t1.*
	FROM Clanci t1, #TempClanci t2
	WHERE t1.ClanakID = t2.ClanakID
		AND RedniBroj BETWEEN @Offset AND (@Offset + @MaxRows - 1)
	
	DROP TABLE #TempClanci

END

/****** Object:  StoredProcedure [dbo].[fsp_Korisnici_Registration]    Script Date: 26.4.2013. 15:11:13 ******/
SET ANSI_NULLS ON
GO
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON
GO
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[fsp_Korisnici_Registration] 
(
	@Ime NVARCHAR(50),
	@Prezime NVARCHAR(50),
	@Mail NVARCHAR(50),
	@Spol NCHAR(1),
	@DatumRodjenja DATE,
	@KorisnickoIme NVARCHAR(50),
	@LozinkaHash NVARCHAR(50),
	@LozinkaSalt NVARCHAR(50)
)
AS
BEGIN
	INSERT INTO Korisnici
	(
		Ime,
		Prezime,
		Mail,
		Spol,
		DatumRodjenja,
		DatumRegistracije,
		PosljednjaPrijava,
		KorisnickoIme,
		LozinkaHash,
		LozinkaSalt,
		Aktivan,
		DatumIzmjene
	)
	VALUES
	(
		@Ime,
		@Prezime,
		@Mail,
		@Spol,
		@DatumRodjenja,
		GETDATE(),
		GETDATE(),
		@KorisnickoIme,
		@LozinkaHash,
		@LozinkaSalt,
		1,
		GETDATE()
	)

	DECLARE @KorisnikID INT
	SET @KorisnikID = (SELECT @@IDENTITY)

	INSERT INTO KorisniciUloge (KorisnikID, UlogaID, DatumKreiranja, DatumIzmjene) VALUES (@KorisnikID, 2, GETDATE(), GETDATE())
END

/****** Object:  StoredProcedure [dbo].[fsp_Korisnici_SelectByNameMail]    Script Date: 26.4.2013. 15:11:13 ******/
SET ANSI_NULLS ON
GO
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON
GO
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[fsp_Korisnici_SelectByNameMail]
(
	@ImePrezime NVARCHAR(100),
	@Mail NVARCHAR(150),
	@Offset INT,
	@MaxRows INT,
	@TotalRows INT = 0 OUTPUT
)
AS
BEGIN

	CREATE TABLE #TempKorisnici
	(
		RedniBroj INT IDENTITY(0, 1),
		KorisnikID INT
	)
	
	IF @ImePrezime <>  ''
	BEGIN
		INSERT INTO #TempKorisnici(KorisnikID)
		SELECT KorisnikID
		FROM Korisnici
		WHERE ((LOWER(Ime + ' ' + Prezime) like '%' + LOWER(@ImePrezime) + '%') OR
		      ((LOWER(Prezime + ' ' + Ime) like '%' + LOWER(@ImePrezime) + '%'))) AND
			  (@Mail = '' OR LOWER(Mail) like '%' + LOWER(@Mail) + '%')
		ORDER BY Prezime ASC
	END
	ELSE
	BEGIN
		INSERT INTO #TempKorisnici(KorisnikID)
		SELECT KorisnikID
		FROM Korisnici
		WHERE @Mail = '' OR LOWER(Mail) like '%' + LOWER(@Mail) + '%'
		ORDER BY Prezime ASC
	END

	SELECT @TotalRows = @@ROWCOUNT

	SELECT t1.*
	FROM Korisnici t1, #TempKorisnici t2
	WHERE t1.KorisnikID = t2.KorisnikID
		AND RedniBroj BETWEEN @Offset AND (@Offset + @MaxRows - 1)
	
	DROP TABLE #TempKorisnici
	
END

SET ANSI_NULLS ON
GO
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON
GO
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[fsp_getAllOdgovoriZaPitanje]
	@PId int
as
	SELECT CONVERT(VARCHAR(10),O.DatumKreiranja,110) AS Datum, O.Negativni,O.OdgovorID, 
           O.Pozitivni, O.Tekst, K.Ime, K.Prezime, (SELECT COUNT(T1.PitanjeID)
										            FROM Pitanja AS T1
										            WHERE T1.KorisnikID=K.KorisnikID) AS 'UkupnoPitanja',
										           (SELECT COUNT(T1.OdgovorID)
										            FROM Odgovori AS T1
										            WHERE T1.KorisnikID=K.KorisnikID) AS 'UkupnoOdgovora'
	FROM Odgovori AS O join Korisnici AS K ON O.KorisnikID = K.KorisnikID
	WHERE O.PitanjeID = @PId AND Status = 1

INSERT [dbo].[Clanci] ([ClanakID], [Naslov], [Autori], [Tekst], [KljucneRijeci], [VrstaID], [TemaID], [KorisnikID], [Dokument], [Status], [Izmjene], [DatumKreiranja], [DatumIzmjene], [DokumentType], [DokumentPath]) VALUES (2, N'Programming language', N'Wiki', N'<span>A&nbsp;<b>programming language</b>&nbsp;is an&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_language" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">artificial language</a>&nbsp;designed to communicate&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_instruction" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">instructions</a>&nbsp;to a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">machine</a>, particularly a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">computer</a>. Programming languages can be used to create&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Program_%28machine%29" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">programs</a>&nbsp;that control the behavior of a machine and/or to express&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">algorithms</a>&nbsp;precisely.</span><span>The earliest programming languages predate the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_computing_hardware" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">invention of the computer</a>, and were used to direct the behavior of machines such as&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacquard_loom" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Jacquard looms</a>and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Player_piano" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">player pianos</a>.<span>[<i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">citation needed</a></i>]</span>&nbsp;Thousands
 of different programming languages have been created, mainly in the 
computer field, with many being created every year. Most programming 
languages describe computation in an&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperative_programming" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">imperative</a>&nbsp;style, i.e., as a sequence of commands, although some languages, such as those that support&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_programming" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">functional programming</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic_programming" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">logic programming</a>, use alternative forms of description.</span><span>The description of a programming language is usually split into the two components of&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syntax_%28programming_languages%29" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">syntax</a>&nbsp;(form) and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantics" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">semantics</a>&nbsp;(meaning). Some languages are defined by a specification document (for example, the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_%28programming_language%29" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">C</a>&nbsp;programming language is specified by an&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Organization_for_Standardization" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">ISO</a>&nbsp;Standard), while other languages, such as&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Perl</a>&nbsp;5 and earlier, have a dominant&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language_implementation" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">implementation</a>&nbsp;that is used as a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_implementation" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">reference</a>.</span><br><h2>Definitions</h2><span>A programming language is a notation for writing&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_program" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">programs</a>, which are specifications of a computation or&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">algorithm</a>.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-Aaby_2004-1" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[1]</a>&nbsp;Some, but not all, authors restrict the term "programming language" to those languages that can express&nbsp;<i>all</i>&nbsp;possible algorithms.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-Aaby_2004-1" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[1]</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-2" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[2]</a>&nbsp;Traits often considered important for what constitutes a programming language include:</span><ul><li><i>Function and target:</i>&nbsp;A&nbsp;<i>computer programming language</i>&nbsp;is a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_language" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">language</a>&nbsp;used to write&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_program" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">computer programs</a>, which involve a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">computer</a>&nbsp;performing some kind of computation<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-sigplan-3" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[3]</a>&nbsp;or<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">algorithm</a>&nbsp;and possibly control external devices such as&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printer_%28computing%29" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">printers</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disk_drive" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">disk drives</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robot" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">robots</a>,<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-robots-4" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[4]</a>&nbsp;and so on. For example&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PostScript" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">PostScript</a>&nbsp;programs
 are frequently created by another program to control a computer printer
 or display. More generally, a programming language may describe 
computation on some, possibly abstract, machine. It is generally 
accepted that a complete specification for a programming language 
includes a description, possibly idealized, of a machine or processor 
for that language.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-nara2-5" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[5]</a>&nbsp;In
 most practical contexts, a programming language involves a computer; 
consequently, programming languages are usually defined and studied this
 way.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-6" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[6]</a>&nbsp;Programming languages differ from&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">natural languages</a>&nbsp;in
 that natural languages are only used for interaction between people, 
while programming languages also allow humans to communicate 
instructions to machines.</li><li><i>Abstractions:</i>&nbsp;Programming languages usually contain&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstraction_%28computer_science%29" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">abstractions</a>&nbsp;for defining and manipulating&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_structure" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">data structures</a>&nbsp;or controlling the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_flow" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">flow of execution</a>. The practical necessity that a programming language support adequate abstractions is expressed by the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstraction_principle_%28programming%29" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">abstraction principle</a>;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-7" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[7]</a>&nbsp;this principle is sometimes formulated as recommendation to the programmer to make proper use of such abstractions.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-8" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[8]</a></li><li><i>Expressive power:</i>&nbsp;The&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_computation" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">theory of computation</a>&nbsp;classifies languages by the computations they are capable of expressing. All&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turing_completeness" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Turing complete</a>&nbsp;languages can implement the same set of&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">algorithms</a>.&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SQL" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">ANSI/ISO SQL</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charity_%28programming_language%29" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Charity</a>&nbsp;are examples of languages that are not Turing complete, yet often called programming languages.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-9" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[9]</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-10" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[10]</a></li></ul><span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_languages" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Markup languages</a>&nbsp;like&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XML" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">XML</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">HTML</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troff" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">troff</a>, which define&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structured_data" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">structured data</a>, are not generally considered programming languages.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-11" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[11]</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-12" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[12]</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-13" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[13]</a>&nbsp;Programming languages may, however, share the syntax with markup languages if a computational semantics is defined.&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XSLT" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">XSLT</a>, for example, is a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turing_completeness" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Turing complete</a>&nbsp;XML dialect.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-14" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[14]</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-15" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[15]</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-16" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[16]</a>&nbsp;Moreover,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LaTeX" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">LaTeX</a>, which is mostly used for structuring documents, also contains a Turing complete subset.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-17" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[17]</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-18" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[18]</a></span><span>The term&nbsp;<i>computer language</i>&nbsp;is sometimes used interchangeably with programming language.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-19" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[19]</a>&nbsp;However,
 the usage of both terms varies among authors, including the exact scope
 of each. One usage describes programming languages as a subset of 
computer languages.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-20" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[20]</a>&nbsp;In
 this vein, languages used in computing that have a different goal than 
expressing computer programs are generically designated computer 
languages. For instance, markup languages are sometimes referred to as 
computer languages to emphasize that they are not meant to be used for 
programming.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-21" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[21]</a>&nbsp;Another
 usage regards programming languages as theoretical constructs for 
programming abstract machines, and computer languages as the subset 
thereof that runs on physical computers, which have finite hardware 
resources.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language#cite_note-22" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[22]</a>&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_C._Reynolds" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">John C. Reynolds</a>&nbsp;emphasizes that&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_specification" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">formal specification</a>&nbsp;languages
 are just as much programming languages as are the languages intended 
for execution. He also argues that textual and even graphical input 
formats that affect the behavior of a computer are programming 
languages, despite the fact they are commonly not Turing-complete, and 
remarks that ignorance of programming language concepts is the reason 
for many flaws in input formats.</span><br>', N'programming', 4, 1, 5, NULL, 1, NULL, CAST(0x0000A1AB00B3DB03 AS DateTime), CAST(0x0000A1AB00B3DB03 AS DateTime), NULL, NULL)
GO
INSERT [dbo].[Clanci] ([ClanakID], [Naslov], [Autori], [Tekst], [KljucneRijeci], [VrstaID], [TemaID], [KorisnikID], [Dokument], [Status], [Izmjene], [DatumKreiranja], [DatumIzmjene], [DokumentType], [DokumentPath]) VALUES (3, N'ASP.NET', N'Wiki', N'<b>ASP.NET</b>&nbsp;is a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Server-side_scripting" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">server-side</a>&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_application_framework" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Web application framework</a>&nbsp;designed for&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_development" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Web development</a>&nbsp;to produce&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamic_Web_pages" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">dynamic Web pages</a>. It was developed by&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Microsoft</a>&nbsp;to allow&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programmer" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">programmers</a>&nbsp;to build dynamic&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_site" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">web sites</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_application" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">web applications</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_service" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">web services</a>. It was first released in January 2002 with version 1.0 of the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Framework" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">.NET Framework</a>, and is the successor to Microsoft''s&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Active_Server_Pages" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Active Server Pages</a>&nbsp;(ASP) technology. ASP.NET is built on the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Language_Runtime" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Common Language Runtime</a>&nbsp;(CLR), allowing programmers to write ASP.NET code using any supported&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_CLI_languages" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">.NET language</a>. The ASP.NET&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOAP" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">SOAP</a>&nbsp;extension framework allows ASP.NET components to process SOAP messages.<br><h2>History</h2><span>After four years of development, and a series of beta releases in 2000 and 2001, ASP.NET 1.0 was released on January 5, 2002 as part of version 1.0 of the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Framework" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">.NET Framework</a>. Even prior to the release, dozens of books had been written about ASP.NET,<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASP.NET#cite_note-1" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[1]</a>&nbsp;and Microsoft promoted it heavily as part of its platform for Web services. Scott Guthrie became the product unit manager for ASP.NET, and development continued apace, with version 1.1 being released on April 24, 2003 as a part of&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Server_2003" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Windows Server 2003</a>. This release focused on improving ASP.NET''s support for mobile devices.</span><br><h2>Characteristics</h2><span>ASP.NET Web pages, known officially as Web Forms,<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASP.NET#cite_note-2" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[2]</a>&nbsp;are the main building block for application development.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASP.NET#cite_note-macdonald63-3" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[3]</a>&nbsp;Web forms are contained in files with a ".aspx" extension; these files typically contain static (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XHTML" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">X</a>)<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">HTML</a>&nbsp;markup, as well as markup defining server-side Web Controls and User Controls where the developers place all the rc content<span>[<i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">further explanation needed</a></i>]</span>&nbsp;for the Web page. Additionally, dynamic code which runs on the server can be placed in a page within a block&nbsp;&lt;% -- dynamic code -- %&gt;, which is similar to other Web development technologies such as&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PHP" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">PHP</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaServer_Pages" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">JSP</a>, and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Active_Server_Pages" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">ASP</a>. With&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASP.NET_3.5" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">ASP.NET Framework 2.0</a>, Microsoft introduced a new&nbsp;<i>code-behind</i>&nbsp;model which allows static text to remain on the .aspx page, while dynamic code remains in an .aspx.vb or .aspx.cs or .aspx.fs file (depending on the programming language used).</span><br><br>', N'ASP.NET, Microsoft', 4, 1, 5, , 1, NULL, CAST(0x0000A1AB00D45DD7 AS DateTime), CAST(0x0000A1AB00D45DD7 AS DateTime), NULL, N'~/Content/articles/3.docx')

It is used to develop&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Console_application" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">console</a>&nbsp;and<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphical_user_interface" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">graphical user interface</a>&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Application_software" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">applications</a>&nbsp;along with&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Forms" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Windows Forms</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Presentation_Foundation" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">WPF</a>&nbsp;applications,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_site" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">web sites</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_application" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">web applications</a>, and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_service" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">web services</a>&nbsp;in both&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Native_code" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">native code</a>&nbsp;together with&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Managed_code" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">managed code</a>&nbsp;for all platforms supported by&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Windows" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Microsoft Windows</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Mobile" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Windows Mobile</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_CE" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Windows CE</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Framework" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">.NET Framework</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Compact_Framework" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">.NET Compact Framework</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Silverlight" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Microsoft Silverlight</a>.</span><span>Visual Studio includes a&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_editor" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">code editor</a>&nbsp;supporting&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IntelliSense" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">IntelliSense</a>&nbsp;as well as&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_refactoring" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">code refactoring</a>. The integrated&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Visual_Studio_Debugger" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">debugger</a>&nbsp;works both as a source-level debugger and a machine-level debugger. Other built-in tools include a forms designer for building&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GUI" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">GUI</a>applications,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_designer" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">web designer</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Class_(computing)" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">class</a>&nbsp;designer, and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Database_schema" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">database schema</a>&nbsp;designer. It accepts plug-ins that enhance the functionality at almost every levelincluding adding support for&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_control" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">source-control</a>&nbsp;systems (like&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subversion_(software)" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Subversion</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_SourceSafe" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Visual SourceSafe</a>) and adding new toolsets like editors and visual designers for&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain-specific_language" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">domain-specific languages</a>&nbsp;or toolsets for other aspects of the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_development_lifecycle" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">software development lifecycle</a>&nbsp;(like the&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Team_Foundation_Server" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Team Foundation Server</a>&nbsp;client: Team Explorer).</span><span>Visual Studio supports different&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">programming languages</a>&nbsp;by means of language services, which allow the code editor and debugger to support (to varying degrees) nearly any programming language, provided a language-specific service exists. Built-in languages include&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">C</a>/<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">C++</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Visual_Studio#cite_note-5" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[5]</a>&nbsp;(via&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_C%2B%2B" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Visual C++</a>),&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VB.NET" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">VB.NET</a>&nbsp;(via&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_Basic_.NET" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Visual Basic .NET</a>),&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_Sharp_(programming_language)" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">C#</a>&nbsp;(via&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_C_Sharp" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Visual C#</a>), and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F_Sharp_(programming_language)" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">F#</a>&nbsp;(as of Visual Studio 2010<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Visual_Studio#cite_note-6" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">[6]</a>). Support for other languages such as&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M_(programming_language)" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">M</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IronPython" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Python</a>, and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IronRuby" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Ruby</a>&nbsp;among others is available via language services installed separately. It also supports&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XML" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">XML</a>/<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XSLT" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">XSLT</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">HTML</a>/<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XHTML" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">XHTML</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">JavaScript</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cascading_Style_Sheets" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">CSS</a>. Individual language-specific versions of Visual Studio also exist which provide more limited language services to the user: Microsoft Visual Basic, Visual J#, Visual C#, and Visual C++.</span><span>Microsoft provides "Express" editions of its Visual Studio 2010 components Visual Basic, Visual C#, Visual C++, and Visual Web Developer at no cost. Visual Studio 2012, 2010, 2008 and 2005 Professional Editions, along with language-specific versions (Visual Basic, C++, C#, J#) of Visual Studio Express 2010 are available for free to students as downloads via Microsoft''s&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DreamSpark" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">DreamSpark</a>&nbsp;program.</span><br>', N'Programming platform', 4, 1, 5, , 1, NULL, CAST(0x0000A1AB00D4FB97 AS DateTime), CAST(0x0000A1AB00D4FB97 AS DateTime), NULL, N'~/Content/articles/4.docx')
